The early internet in the 1980s through the early 2000s, Web 1.0, was decen=
tralized. It was built on top of a series of open protocols that anyone cou=
ld build directly on top of, like HTTP for websites, SMTP for email, SMS fo=
r messaging, IRC for chat, and FTP for file transfer. The benefit was that =
these protocols were generally agreed upon and not subject to change; I cou=
ld build a website on HTTP and if people had my website address, they could=
 go directly to my site, not intermediated by anyone else.=C2=A0
As Dixon said, =E2=80=9CThis meant that people or organizations could grow =
their internet presence knowing the rules of the game wouldn=E2=80=99t chan=
ge later on.=E2=80=9D It was a direct relationship between creator and cons=
umer. There were some major challenges, though:=C2=A0
Stateless. Web 1.0 protocols were stateless, meaning that they didn=E2=80=
=99t capture state, or user data. =E2=80=9CCapturing user data=E2=80=9D has=
 negative connotations today, but stateless protocols meant that website ow=
ners didn=E2=80=99t even know whether I=E2=80=99d visited a site before, an=
d couldn=E2=80=99t tailor experiences accordingly.=C2=A0
Too Technical. You needed to be technical to build a presence on Web 1.0, w=
hich meant that regular people were left out.=C2=A0
Missing Protocols. Web 1.0 didn=E2=80=99t have standard protocols for many =
of the things that power the internet today: payments, search, apps, social=
 media, commerce, credit, and more.
Protocols Didn=E2=80=99t Make Money! Imagine developing HTTP, seeing trilli=
ons of dollars worth of value being built on top of it, and not being able =
to participate in the upside aside from some speaking fees, consulting gigs=
, and book sales. Oof.=C2=A0
Web 2.0 (mid-2000s to present) emerged as entrepreneurs recognized the hole=
s in Web 1.0 and built products to fill them in, and capture the value in t=
he process. These companies didn=E2=80=99t just capture state, they aggrega=
ted it, building up huge troves of valuable user data. They made it so that=
 anyone could participate and build a presence -- think about how easy it i=
s to set up a Facebook page versus coding a website. They wrapped existing =
protocols in frictionless user interfaces and created de facto products whe=
re no protocols existed. Sheng describes the transition:
State aggregators became the dominant players of the internet and one surpr=
ising result of Internet 2.0 is that many of the original open protocols ha=
ve been replaced by state aggregators. Internet 2.0 also showed us the powe=
r of networks. In the absence of open protocols, state aggregators acted as=
 protocols for new areas.=C2=A0
Web 2.0 is fucking awesome. I=E2=80=99m writing this newsletter to you beca=
use of Web 2.0. The probability of me figuring out how to write to all of y=
ou directly on top of SMTP is exactly 0.00%, and many of you found Not Bori=
ng through state aggregators like Twitter.=C2=A0
But there are challenges, too. Twitter, for example, could decide to shut d=
own my account whenever it wants to, and I can=E2=80=99t take any of my fol=
lowers with me. It did so to the President of the United States (my take: t=
here was no good solution, they chose the best among bad options). In a les=
s charged example, Facebook famously allowed brands and publishers to build=
 up audiences on a seemingly free platform, and then changed the rules, for=
cing them to pay to reach their own audiences.=C2=A0
Dixon describes the transition as an S-curve. In the beginning, centralized=
 platforms do anything they can to attract users, developers, and businesse=
s in order to build up multi-sided network effects.=C2=A0
Once they=E2=80=99ve built those network effects, though, and they know tha=
t users, developers, and businesses are locked in, they switch from =E2=80=
=9Cattract=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cextract.=E2=80=9D The easiest way to grow r=
evenue is to start charging businesses and developers to reach customers, a=
nd to serve customers ads or products based on the data they=E2=80=99ve acc=
umulated.=C2=A0
To be clear, I don=E2=80=99t think there=E2=80=99s anything inherently evil=
 in this. I could leave Twitter if I felt that I was getting screwed, and i=
ndeed, many people deleted Facebook after the Cambridge Analytica scandal a=
nd after many incidents since then.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s a market. The way the internet is currently architected allows=
 for companies to capture value, and they do.=C2=A0
Web3, then, isn=E2=80=99t as much an idealistic repudiation of Web 2.0 (alt=
hough that=E2=80=99s a good marketing tool) as much as it is a natural evol=
ution of the market made possible by new technology.=C2=A0
Web3 is the next version of the internet, built on top of crypto-economic n=
etworks, like Bitcoin and Ethereum. According to Dixon, =E2=80=9CCryptonetw=
orks combine the best features of the first two internet eras: community-go=
verned, decentralized networks with capabilities that will eventually excee=
d those of the most advanced centralized services.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
At the heart of Web3 is the idea of consensus protocols and standards with =
money baked in. I think about it like a series of open source APIs [https:/=
/email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkEFuxCAMRU8z7CbCJCRkwaKbXiMi4CZ0CETgdJTbl06kV=
pVss_iyP_9ZQ7ikfOo9FWI_Y6JzRx3xWQISYWZHwTx5p6EXqpXdyJzuHCipmC_TR0bcjA-a8oFs=
P-bgrSGf4muDcyHZqvsWrTTOKY7D2Cne9ij7AXowHK0Ffvmaw3mMFjV-YT5TRBb0SrSXW_t2E--=
1YqI5ZR-XphxzIWMfjU1bFfbaZvflbkK404r3pznvLj0j81pwARyEhPp36Bto0mwAwmA_4dbxbR=
H_jrGsf12q_FjNhuEl1GxTfbcjejonjGYO6K7YdNF7gZgWjJgrVTcZqswApBJK9iO0V8zKpYVBj=
UJ1rDq7VLfin-k3NXeISQ] that anyone can use to build according to an agreed =
upon set of rules, that gain financial value over time which is shared with=
 everyone who contributes to the API.=C2=A0
Instead of building siloed products, Web3 is built for interoperability. Th=
is is a key concept, keep it in mind. Decentralized Finance (=E2=80=9CDeFi=
=E2=80=9D), which, as the name implies, is attempting to build a new financ=
ial system without central financial institutions, is one of the most promi=
sing layers being built on Web3. A common analogy for the way DeFi products=
 are built is with =E2=80=9Cmoney legos.=E2=80=9D In a 2019 post, Building =
with Money Legos [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMuOhCAQRb-m2bWxUGxc=
sJjN_IbhUSrTCAaL6fj3Q7eLSQgVUrncnGM14ZLyqfZ0EHtfE507qoivIyARZlYOzJN3CgYuO9G=
PzKnegRSS-WOaM-KmfVCUC7K9mOCtJp_iJ9G2XLBVudkZ1_YIDkY9Ax-1ta6breX9oEU7Xr26OI=
_RosJfzGeKyIJaifbj1n3d-Hc9GzpftsamrT4oUcA6TfHB-bjcX57W-1Zz5z1UpuOuzdBpITU-h=
p55xVsOLXABFQKGBppkNEB42B-49e228OYo5iBtn-8GllVMZFKuX9f1c9Ubhs-iQk51biV6OieM=
2gR0Fz9dGj9GpgUj5qrXTZqqPAAhuRTDCN3FWwV18JAjlz2rzS7VVPwv_QPN5ou2], DeFi com=
pany Totle wrote:
There are roughly 200 projects listed on DeFi Prime [https://email.mg2.subs=
tack.com/c/eJxFUMtuxCAM_JrlGGHyIgcOvfQ3EAGTpSUQgdMqf192c6hk2bJGo3lYQ7jlcqkj=
V2Kvpek6UCX8rRGJsLCzYtHBKZiE7MdhYU4NDuQoWajaF8TdhKionMiOc43BGgo5vRmci5E91cq=
tN8Yu3s8TF72duEc-WwfCG8mdu3XN6QImiwp_sFw5IYvqSXTUR__xEJ9tHPpwlLBjZ_PefhaU4A=
I4iBGaM5g66PJqAOJsv-Ax8H0TXT3XSsZ-vzisqJRpzSWkrcHfT7NjfAPNuW53P1OgS2Mya0R3h=
6K7m3dMvWHC0jpz2lBrBGCUQo7TAv0doqXuYZaLkANryi43VvoX_QMaiXzD] alone, each wi=
th their own unique features and infrastructure. This means that if you pic=
ked any 3 out of the roughly 200 listed tools, you=E2=80=99d have 1,313,400=
 different combinations to choose from to build a new financial product.
That mirrors one of the benefits of APIs that I wrote about, namely:
There is also a competitive advantage to be gained from how you leverage AP=
Is to build your company and product.=C2=A0
Using a bunch of APIs that are really flexible, and figuring out good ways =
to connect them, leads to a combinatorial explosion of potential workflows.=
 API-first companies turn software into like customizable building blocks.
There=E2=80=99s a reason for the similarity. Web3, too, uses APIs for softw=
are to talk to each other.=C2=A0
Source: readthedocs.io
The main differences between Web 2.0 and Web3 are Levels 0-2, and the impli=
cations of the architecture on where the value accrues within the system.=
=C2=A0
While some people love the privacy that Web3 offers, or the fact that =E2=
=80=9Cthe man=E2=80=9D will no longer own your data, that gets it backwards=
 in my opinion. It=E2=80=99s not about who doesn=E2=80=99t own your data, b=
ut who does: you. That=E2=80=99s what crypto folks call =E2=80=9CSelf-Sover=
eign Identity.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Despite the large sums of money made by the people who own Bitcoin, Ethereu=
m, and other altcoins, I=E2=80=99ve always viewed the Web3 movement as anti=
-capitalist. That couldn=E2=80=99t be further from the truth. The movement =
is really about doing one of the most capitalist things there is: cutting o=
ut the middleman. It means that instead of value accruing to the Aggregator=
s, there can be a more direct connection between suppliers and consumers.=
=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s not about taking money out of the system, it=E2=80=99s about m=
oving the money around to the people who create and the people who consume,=
 and to the people who maintain and improve the network itself. And it=E2=
=80=99s about attaching each user=E2=80=99s data and money directly to them=
 (Self-Sovereign Identity), creating a public record that they own what the=
y own (blockchain), and letting them take it with them, and profit from it,=
 wherever they go on the web (Interoperability).=C2=A0
To learn more about Web3 and NFTs, the Direct-to-Avatar Economy, and the Va=
lue Chain of the Open Metaverse:
