"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Th=
e early internet in the 1980s through the early 2000s, <strong>Web 1.0</str=
ong>, was decentralized. It was built on top of a series of open <strong>pr=
otocols</strong> that anyone could build directly on top of, like HTTP for =
websites, SMTP for email, SMS for messaging, IRC for chat, and FTP for file=
 transfer. The benefit was that these protocols were generally agreed upon =
and not subject to change; I could build a website on HTTP and if people ha=
d my website address, they could go directly to my site, not intermediated =
by anyone else.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">As Dixon said, &#8220;This meant that peo=
ple or organizations could grow their internet presence knowing the rules o=
f the game wouldn&#8217;t change later on.&#8221; It was a direct relations=
hip between creator and consumer. There were some major challenges, though:=
&nbsp;</p><ul style=3D"margin: 1em 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px=
 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>Stateless.</strong> Web 1.0 p=
rotocols were stateless, meaning that they didn&#8217;t capture state, or u=
ser data. &#8220;Capturing user data&#8221; has negative connotations today=
, but stateless protocols meant that website owners didn&#8217;t even know =
whether I&#8217;d visited a site before, and couldn&#8217;t tailor experien=
ces accordingly.&nbsp;</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; =
mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>Too Technical.</strong> You needed to=
 be technical to build a presence on Web 1.0, which meant that regular peop=
le were left out.&nbsp;</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px;=
 mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0;"><strong>Missing Protocols. </strong>Web 1.0 =
didn&#8217;t have standard protocols for many of the things that power the =
internet today: payments, search, apps, social media, commerce, credit, and=
 more.</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-form=
at: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0;"><strong>Protocols Didn&#8217;t Make Money!</strong> Imagine d=
eveloping HTTP, seeing trillions of dollars worth of value being built on t=
op of it, and not being able to participate in the upside aside from some s=
peaking fees, consulting gigs, and book sales. Oof.&nbsp;</p></li></ul><p s=
tyle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em=
 0;"><strong>Web 2.0</strong> (mid-2000s to present) emerged as entrepreneu=
rs recognized the holes in Web 1.0 and built products to fill them in, and =
capture the value in the process. These companies didn&#8217;t just capture=
 state, they aggregated it, building up huge troves of valuable user data. =
They made it so that anyone could participate and build a presence -- think=
 about how easy it is to set up a Facebook page versus coding a website. Th=
ey wrapped existing protocols in frictionless user interfaces and created d=
e facto products where no protocols existed. Sheng describes the transition=
:</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;"><=
p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 =
1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em>State aggregators became the dominant players=
 of the internet and one surprising result of Internet 2.0 is that many of =
the original open protocols have been replaced by state aggregators. Intern=
et 2.0 also showed us the power of networks. In the absence of open protoco=
ls, state aggregators acted as protocols for new areas.&nbsp;</em></p></blo=
ckquote><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=3D"font-size:=
