state aggregators like Twitter.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">But there are challenges,=
 too. Twitter, for example, could decide to shut down my account whenever i=
t wants to, and I can&#8217;t take any of my followers with me. It did so t=
o the President of the United States (my take: there was no good solution, =
they chose the best among bad options). In a less charged example, Facebook=
 famously allowed brands and publishers to build up audiences on a seemingl=
y free platform, and then changed the rules, forcing them to pay to reach t=
heir own audiences.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; l=
